05% 106 Vi\nVanadium Corn fis 1941 84% 8,\nVertientes Sugar Co 7s 1942 10% 12\nWabash Rwy Co fis 1939 _ 61 64%\nWarner Bros 6s 1939 _ ig <9%\nWest N Y ft Pa 4a 1943 107% 108\nFOREIGN EXCHANGES.\nQuotations furnished by W. B. Hlbbs ft Co.\nNominal gold Checks\nvalue. today.\nLondon, pound-$4.8665 S5.00A\nParis, franc 3gl%c 3.39%c\nBrussels, betas-\u00bb- Ii3-Sic 12\u00a7S?4C\nBerlin, .mark_23.82e\nRome, lira _,5.26c 5.26%e\nZurich. Irane 19.3c 23.16%c\nAthens, drachma- 1.3c\nMadrid, peseta _19.3c\nVienna, schilling_-t\nBudapest, pengo 1 49c\nPrague, crown <nom)_ 2.9640\nWarsaw, rloty -11-22c -z\nCopenhagen. crowh-26.8c __.33%e\nOslo! crown -~6.8c .Tc inL.\nStockholm. crown 26.8c -5.79%c\nMontreal. 1-128 Per cent premium.\nPRICE OF LEAD BOOSTED.\nNEW YORK. Jan. 11 UP)-\u2014The\nAmerican Smelting Js Refining Co.\nraised the price of lead today $1 a\nton to the hula o( 4.90 ceng a pound,\nNew York.\nISHELD1TIM\u2019\nHas Little or No Relation\nto General Business\nOutlook.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 11 (N.A.N.A.).\u2014\nThe current upswing in stock prices,\nit is important to keep In mind, is\nlargely in the nature of a rebound\ngrowing out of the situation in the\nmarket itself and bearing little or no\nrelation to the outlook for general\nbusiness. Casting about for an ex\nplanation, it is natural for writers of\nmarket reports to credit the rise to the\nprospect of heavy armament expendi\ntures and/or to the old familiar talk\nof \u201cinflation.\u201d But our armament ex\npenditures have been unusually high\nfor several years past, and the evi\ndence is all against \"inflation.\u201d\nSome encouragement was derived\nfrom another increase in the opkrating\nrate of the steel industry as estimated\nfor this week by the Iron and Steel\nInstitute. That estimate puts the\nrate back at about the level of the first\nweek in December, which appeared low\nenough at the time.\nmore Rename views.\nAs to the business outlook, views of\nbusiness leaders at this stage are likely\nto be more reliable than those of mar\nket followers, whose optimism is\nlargely derived from the upward course\nof prices on the stock tape.\nLammont du Pont, chairman of E.\nI. du Pont de Nemours Co., evident\nly does not go along with those who\nare looking for general business to re\ncover as swiftly as if nothing has hap\npened to give it a severe jolting. He\ntold the Senate committee investigat\ning unemployment that the \"forecast\nof sales for the first six months of\n1938 is 23 per cent less than in the\nfirst six months of 1937.\u201d He said\nfurther that he could not be \"too hope\nful of increased employment in our\ncompany, for it is evident that we are\nin a pronounced recession.\"\nMr. du Pont's figure on sales jibes\npretty well with a recent forecast of\nindustrial production made by the,\nStandard Statistics Co. Based on\ntentative estimates, that organization\nsaid it expected the index of indus\ntrial production for the current quar\nter to average about 75\u2014a drop of\nmore than 25 per cent from the first\nquarter of 1937 and moderately below\nthe first three months of 1936. \"This\nforecast,\u201d says the summary, \"make*\nfull allowance for a moderate recovery\nin aggregate business activity in Feb\nruary and March.\u201d\ntew level oi as rer icni.\nEvidence is still being educed as to\nthe severity of the industrial decline.\nThe January bulletin of the Federal\nReserve System says that the index\nof industrial production dropped to a\nlow level of about 83 per cent of the\n1923-1925 average in December. In\nNovember the index was 89. and the\naverage for the first eight months\nof 1937 was 116. The high for last\nyear was set in April and May. with\nthe index at 118 for both months. In\nAugust a brief upturn in activity\nbrought the index bade to the 118\nlevel. But at no time during last year\ndid the index equal the 1936 peak\nof 121, which was set in December\nof that year.\nThe level of 83, estimated for the\nlast month of last year, is the lowest\nseen since the latter part of 1934, and\nis below the best of that year, as well\nas below the best of 1933. The mid\nsummer \u201cinflation boom\" of 1933 sent\nthe index kiting to 100, but it later\ncame dowA as fast as it had risen.\n(Copyright. 1938.)\nNEW YORK BAR SILVER.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 11 WP).\u2014Bar sil\nver, 44 V unchanged.\n91-DAY TREASURY BILLS\nBRING AVERAGE OF 99.76\nB) the Associated Press.\nSecretary of the Treasury Morgen\nthau said last night the weekly sale\nof $50,000,000 worth of 91-day Treas\nury bills brought an average price of\n99.76, equivalent to borrowing money\nat .097 per cent. Last week, the bills i\nsold for an average of 99.984, one of\nthe highest prices in recent years.\n4 ___\nNEW YORK BANK STOCKS\nNEW YORK. Jan. 11 OP).\u2014Over-the-\ncounter market bank and trust, companies\n\u2014opening bid and asked prices:\nBid Asked.\nBk of Msnhattan <1*4) 223< 24'4\nChase (1.40) _ 34'a 3f\u00bbVa\nCity (1) ..._ \"M.\u00ab 30>/\u00ab\nCommercial (R) 140 152\nFirst. National (100)_1810 1850\nPublic (1 'a) 34 37\nBankers (2) _._ 50 52\nBrooklyn Trust (4) _ 80 04\nCentral Hanover (4)_ OO'a Oil1,4\nChemical (1.801 _ 45 4 7\nContinental (.80) 12'a 14\nCorn Exchange (3) _ 8.V,\u00ab SO1/*\nEmpire (1 _ _ 22 23\nGuaranty (12) _ 258 203\nIrving (OOi 12*4 13>4\nLawyers Trust (1.40)_ 28 33\nManufacturers (2) __ 38 4n\nN Y Trust (5) 04 07\nTitle Guar A: Trust O'* 7Va\nReserve District No 5.\nREPORT OF CONDITION OP THE\nIndustrial Bank of Washington\nOf Wasnington. D. C.. at the close of busi\nness on December 31 1937.\nPublished in response to call made by\nComptroller of the Currency under Sec\ntion 5211, U. 8. Revised Statutes.\nASSETS\n1. Loans and discounts *221.168.08\n2. Overdrafts 5.03\n3. United States Government\nobligations direct and\nfully guaranteed 79.560 03\n4. Other bonds- stocks and\nsecurities 161.675.43\n6. Banking house. $37 445.37;\nfurniture and fixtures.\n$7,460.04 39.905.36\nReal estate owned other\nthan banking house